Paramesh Gopi - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Sure. Two things, that we bring, one is for the first time, we're actually bringing you E7 class memory, so you have eight channels of DDR4, you can support a terabyte per socket. Along with really, really, robust high-end E5 class core. So we've actually essentially done our own version of collapsing two large pieces of performance into one die, right. So, with X-Gene 3, you have from a technology point of view something that converges the need of all of our hyperscale customers which is to de-constraint memory and compute performance, number one.

Number two, with X-Gene 3XL we talked about. I mean by the way one other thing before I move on. I made this in my prepared comments. We're essentially taking a 2P system and putting it on one die, with X-Gene 3, Suji. And then, we've gone one step further and we talked about the announcement of the technology that comes after X-Gene 3 which is X-Gene 3XL, where we essentially are able to do 64 cores on one die, right. So, what we are essentially doing is really making sure that from a technology perspective, we're going to offer the absolutely top class performance for ARM compute along with no constraints or as little constraints as possible on the memory sub-system supported for a single physical implementation of the socket. Does that kind of makes sense?
