Operator
We have a follow up question from Matt Ramsay from Canaccord. Your line is open.
Matthew D. Ramsay - Canaccord Genuity, Inc.
Yeah. Paramesh, thanks for let me jump back in. The PAM4 sort of sponsored or semi-custom design that your guys are doing, maybe you could just talk to us philosophically about that type of engagement, right. So why pursue that type of engagement versus just interacting with the customer and pursuing a roadmap? Why are they willing to pay upfront, it's a very different revenue model from what you guys – I mean, as you mentioned some others in the industry have done that, but it's something new for your team? So, just maybe a little bit around that and just if there is any weird accounting or anything that goes along with that, because it's a little bit different and it's obviously impacting the margins quite a bit. So I just think sort of little clarity there might be helpful. Thank you.
Paramesh Gopi - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
So, can I maybe start by saying that this is not a strange model for the company. I'll remind you, if you go back five years Alcatel-Lucent, I can tell you this because it was five years ago used to pay us to build CSSPs for them, other big optical companies have done the same, where we can have a version of it, that we can sell commercially and a version of it that we can customize for them. So, a) the model is not new to the company. What is new to the company is the mixed-signal technology that we're bringing to this whole market.
So let me take a step back. I'll go back and tell you that the key to the optical connectivity market in the data center are the ability to get the lowest power per gigabit per second of traffic optical module into a faceplate of a switch or a cluster – into a faceplate at the top of the rack switch or a cluster switch. In other words, the traffic is growing at a hyper-exponential rate. I mean if you look at Cisco's estimates or Google's estimates, you can see that, right? So 100-gig today exists in the form of a very big 4-by-25 or 3-by-40 or 2-by-50 type of solution, which does not fit into a QSFP type form factor and a power that is anywhere between 4 and 6 watts per port.

Now let's look at where things are going. It's pretty clear that this is going to be the year of 50-gig Ethernet ports on switches, right. That's happening. The switch market is moving there. It's also pretty clear that the rate at which traffic is going, several clusters are going to have multi-terabit switches that are going to be connecting them together. That's already happened in some of the big data centers. It's going to happen across both the data center and the enterprise.
So what did we do and why are we in this pole position? Three years ago, we made the bet that we wanted to take all of our fundamental long-haul Forward Error Correction IP, all of our A2D and D2A technology that we've developed for things that are lower rates like the 10-gigabit rate, or the 40-gigabit rate or the 28-gigabit rate, all of SerDes components and then move them to FinFET as well as move the fundamental, programmable DSP engine that we had to accommodate these types of functions for 16-nanometer FinFET.
So the end of that entire IP creation process was somewhere in the fall of last year. A bunch of customers, including end data center operators, wanted to see this kind of working, because they couldn't believe that we could move all this IP at a particular power point and get them what they wanted. So, now as soon as we showed what we were able to do between the optics maturing, between people wanting the higher densities at the lowest possible power, at the lowest possible cost, they basically said, well, you guys are the only ones with proven IP, and so what they did was, in one fell swoop, all of the people who were going to ship millions of units over the next three to five years, decided that they needed to partner with us. Does that answer the question?
Matthew D. Ramsay - Canaccord Genuity, Inc.
Yeah, and that's helpful for context. I appreciate the patience. Thanks.
Paramesh Gopi - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
No problem.
Operator
We have a second follow-up question from the line of Hans Mosesmann from Raymond James. Your line is open.
Hans C. Mosesmann - Raymond James & Associates, Inc.
Yeah, thanks. Hey, Paramesh, can you give us a sense of the state of the connectivity market, the end-market data center versus the service provider, what's happening out there as you engage with customers just on an ongoing basis?
Paramesh Gopi - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Sure. I think it's pretty clear that – let me start with the data center first and I'll get to the service provider. It's pretty clear that every data center guy that we've talked to or that has engaged with us today have – and in their minds once we showed them the 100-gig technology, they're like, okay, where is 400-gig? So people are already starting to move their entire focus to saying, you've now demonstrated 100-gig working; we're going to go now and move this to more of a – okay, it's the technology piece of it is done, you guys are on the path to develop really compelling customizations for various high-volume applications. How do we now bring your focus to 400-gig?
Because when you have a bunch of 100-gig front ports on a switch, you need something to aggregate them all, so the next big logical alternative is 400-gig, right. So a data center guy today, if you talk to the leading guys who are shipping – I'm not talking about shipping 10,000 units for data center interconnect between data centers. I'm talking about guys who basically run a million servers, okay. All those guys are basically telling us, guys, we need to accelerate 400-gig. First of all, get 100-gig done – you guys are done, let's go focus on 400-gig. That's where the state of the industry and the customer traction is today. 100-gig is yesterday's – as far as they're concerned, we have a path, we know the cost points, we're going to deal with it. You guys are it.

Now, how do we build 400-gig? That's where everybody's focused on, in terms of optics, in terms of mixed signal, in terms of SerDes et cetera. Spending there, Hans, continues unabated. In fact I'll quote a very large data center operator, and he told me this less than six weeks ago he said, if you guys had a 100-gig a year ago, I would have used it, I would be buying it. So, they're not waiting – I mean they want the higher rates, right. That's number one.
Number two, as far as the service provider is concerned, I think it's interesting to see a lot of the service provider equipment that people like Alcatel and Cisco are building, being consumed by data center operators or being consumed by the service provisioning piece of AT&T or Verizon, that deals with the data center operators. You know that Verizon had a major contract that's happened this summer, that's really helped. We talked about it in the past. It has had a very positive effect on these margins as you can see today. We also see the peering points that AT&T has with guys like Amazon or Facebook, starting to use more and more carrier class equipment or packet optical equipment where our chips are being designed in.
So, fundamentally, I think you'll see the data center market driving, and the service provider market following. And you'll see service provider platform is being used in the data center market and vice versa in the future. Does that kind of makes sense?
Hans C. Mosesmann - Raymond James & Associates, Inc.
Yeah. It does. It does. Another question if I can? Was there any impact to the ZTE situation that was announced in early March?
Paramesh Gopi - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Go ahead, Marty.
Martin S. McDermut - Chief Financial Officer
Yeah. Well, the issue has been resolved, I think, we do sell to ZTE, we said that the revenues are about mid single digits to us. Right now, the issues have been resolved. We are shipping to them and recognizing revenue. If that changes, if the U.S. Government decides to cut them off again, it's possible that we're going to have an impact to our results. However, somebody else would probably going to step in and start shipping product, if they drop out of a market, but right now, it's business as usual and we are not aware of any other issues out there at this point.
Hans C. Mosesmann - Raymond James & Associates, Inc.
Okay. Thank you very much.
Paramesh Gopi - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Thanks, Hans.
Operator
Thank you. At this time, I'm showing no further questions. I would now like to turn the call back over to Paramesh Gopi for closing remarks.
Paramesh Gopi - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Yeah. Thank you all for taking the time and have a good day.
Operator
Ladies and gentlemen, thank you for participating in today's conference. This does conclude today's program. You may all disconnect. Everyone have a great day.
