Paramesh Gopi
So Cody just to give me some more clarity -- you can see how strong our connected business have been -- it's been a phenomenal quarter for us. I also recognize that team actually consistently moved our margin profile up which is what we said we were going to do and we were -- we are continuing to drive that going forward because our new products that be ramping extremely good margin profile on both sides of the business.
Cody Acree
Paramesh, if we can switch gears -- I guess and help us maybe understand some of the impact of some of your announcements this quarter, specifically around the IEEE standard. How did that come about? What does that mean for the world? How does that accelerate things and how do we put some kind of volume estimates around?
Paramesh Gopi
Very good question. So I think there has been a lot of talk about PAM4 for the last -- probably two years. And really people have essentially used that in a in a loose way to talk about multiple types of optical module solution. For the first time, I think there is a significant two move towards changing the module landscape going forward to have a single-laser 100-gigabit per second; and the only way you can do that in a sub four to five module is to have in fact advanced DSP technology, and advanced mixed signal analog technology, all come together with photonics. So I think there has been a lot of talk about PAM4. We have -- we now have taken all of -- probably three and a half years' worth of work that we have done and have led the industry from a development point-of-view. And it was our solution that catalyzed a move to standardize the technology across module form factors and module members.
What does that do? First of all it renders the two laser and four solutions, rather important going forward. Second, it starts to really build a new ecosystem of 100 and 40-gig type modules in 2017. We've always said that this is going to happen, people are paying us to build semi-custom solutions for volumes, and now you have a standards body that's going to make it a mandate. So what does that do for us? It puts us on a very nice track to having a very clear visible growth pattern over the next few years. And it's no longer determined by elastic factors that are beyond our control but mostly, all now driven by standards and we probably have in my opinion -- two-year lead on anybody else. So we stand to gain and poised to gain a very -- expect to gain a very good share of this market as it evolves.

Cody Acree
And then lastly, the workload orders that you received last quarter -- you talked about last quarter, have you used follow-on orders or any feedback that you can talk about just how is that -- those first workload orders starting to shape up?
Paramesh Gopi
So Cody, can you rewind? When you say workload, can you be more specific.
Cody Acree
Well, you announced on the last call that you have received your first workload orders; production server orders for X-Gene and you talked about two different customers; service provider and data center operator. I'm just wondering what the feedback has been from the customers? Have they come in and ordered more, just what is the statement here?
Paramesh Gopi
They are doing, the feedback is definitely we mentioned one of them in our prepared remarks; they are fully in the production traffic phases, so this is now real-time in their yield production environment and so that's a huge validation of the technology and it's robustness and the other engagement proceeding just as we expected and we are very pleased with the progress on it.
Operator
And our next question comes from the line of Matt Ramsay with Canaccord Genuity. Your line is now open.
