Paramesh Gopi
Sure, just to be clear right, I mean this is going to be the actual first and most significant part from an ARM 64 perspective that will have the ability to compete with Skylink [ph] and we have talked about this over the last quarter or quarter and half, we have actually had many announcements and many I will call it [indiscernible] in terms of what it can do. I recognize that we see very wide interest all the way from where our existing customers where mega data center operators to enterprise type folks like HPE who are already shipping actually one type programs with us. But our focus [Technical Difficulty] to be clear is that mega data center kind of market and I believe that it has all of the right features from a memory addressability perspective from a technology TDP perspective to essentially really be right in the middle of a [indiscernible] class processor.
So from our prospective that's what we have always targeted, we're very, very happy to say that now the chips and the fab are on track to whatever we expected to do last quarter. Finally I think we have always maintained that you won't see [indiscernible] revenue have any big impact until our fiscal '18.

Steven Smigie
And I assume you could talk a little bit more about PAM4, my sense there is that there have some question marks about how big PAM4 is going to be for a 100G but that as we get to 200 and above it has to go to PAM4, and there is some that I think they are starting to suggest that maybe 100-G even won't be that long of a cycle and 200-G maybe coming more quickly than anticipated. So I think that sort of sets you guys up very well that doesn't need turn out to be true and we have to turn the PAM4 and obviously with -- you would be in a strong position to really capitalize on that. So I was hoping you could comment a little bit what you see as a percentage of 100-G and PAM4 and how quickly or maybe 200G could come?
Paramesh Gopi
Let me just make, first of all good question. Two things, when we look at PAM4 adoption look at what drives it? It's basically space played [ph] density in a rack. So rack has a fixed amount of power between 2 and 2.5 kilowatts. It has X number of 50-gig or 100-gig Ethernet port. And so at some level that fiber and plumbing in a rack and between rack and between data centers goes in the numbers like one and four. So there is no -- I mean for us a 200-gig solution is definitely viable but when we did -- when we looked at it, it was 100-gig and 400-gig, those were the two things that are going to straddle the growth in this market.
Why? Look at graphic statistics that Cisco puts out every month. I mean we're getting hyper exponential growth of traffic in all of these data centers networks. There is probably three to five new data centers being built every year with roughly about half a million to million servers each over a million square feet of data center, right. So really speaking, we're looking at 100-gig solutions that are more short span and 400-gig solutions that are more long-stand. And fundamentally, these two things are only possible if you have 100-gig base working with DST and the CMOS analog front-end. So that gives you some color on what it takes to participate in 100-gig and 400-gig.
The other big thing that I think cause the standard to go really fast was -- today the pricing of a module, the producability of the module are all depending on the manufacturing yield. This is common sense but sometimes gets ignored; more optics, more problems; more power, less yield. Smaller number of lasers, better yield, less cost and more power. So that's what this technology is going to be critical in driving into the data center in terms of size. If you take the entire market to be between 500 million and 750 million, that includes all the four lambda, 4/25 meet -- 8/25, all of these different feeds; and you say well, what percentage of data centers will switch to it.
Look at it option; they go anywhere between 10% and 30% over the first two years. As I said earlier in my comments, with the standardization we can easily cut that down by factor. I hope that helps.
Steven Smigie
Great. And last question was just -- I think you got a nice win there with 8-key. I believe that was on X-Gene1 and obviously we're very excited about X-Gene3 but to get a X-Gene1 – can you give a little bit more color, any rental wins there? And for that matter, on X-Gene2 as well that we see a potential contraction as customers think?
Paramesh Gopi
Good question, we are very excited about this whole storage platform because for the first time people talked about various feed volume and this is an example of how you see an important volume marker in the ARM space. So there is no better proof than you going -- than you looking at customers -- HPs and customers, the likes of UPS or FedEx or Walmart buying the stuff. Now you're moving this into mainstream. You know, this is what from a maturity perspective Steve, it shows what it takes to go run into a mainstream enterprise platform, and we're very proud because from an ARM technology perspective, I don't think any of the other ARM vendors have had this level of success. And by the way we're having this success with X-Gene1. So you can imagine the potential that lies in X-Gene3.

Steven Smigie
Okay, thank you.
Operator
Thank you. And our next question comes from the line of Rick Schafer with Oppenheimer. Your line is now open.
