Paramesh Gopi
I think this is a good base; if you look at the past two -- I mean the guide for this; I mean the actual results for the quarter and the quarter, a good day's work off of what can drive it up and down and any additional tape-ups that we have that we expense and those can run into each one about $1.5 million if we have some project cost in new project introduction cost. So this is -- we're aiming the R&D spend pretty stable except for that -- except for that variable that depends on our new product activity and I think that from what we've talked about the product that are going to come onboard.
Martin McDermut
Yes. So I think another way to look at it is that -- what will change is primarily is math ending up.
Operator
Thank you. [Operator Instructions] And our next question comes from the line of Chris Rollins with Hanna [ph] International Group. Your line is now open.
Unidentified Analyst
Hey guys, congrats on a really nice quarter here. So, long-term you guys think maybe a year out -- something like that. I know the simple questions on this but how should we think about compute -- should we think about this as a new steady state or a bounce back. I mean it is like mid-teens revenue per quarter like a real number. And then for connectivity, is this kind of a one-time thing or is this a new steady state or could we even grow from this level as we work out like into next year? I mean I think our heads are turning to spending with all those volatility in your segments. So any kind of clues you could give us would be great.
Paramesh Gopi
Sure. I think from our perspective Chris, we don't guide more than one quarter out but just to give you the notion of the connectivity business; these new products, if you really look at it; we have a secured Ethernet product line that is really ramping well. We have huge momentum in terms of our OTN and five products. And we've talked about this for the last four quarters in terms of our leadership positions from a technology perspective on PAM4 which then converted over the people doing semi-custom engagements with the likes of what they would [ph]. So we are planning for sustainability and been driving growth momentum on the connectivity business. So none of -- when you asked about is this a one quarter, two quarter phenomenon; I want to look -- if you really think about it what drove this quarter is stuff that is all centered around -- that's the way you want to be, right.
On the computer side, we've always thought that our PC is kind of in the structural decline; we've maintained that for a long time and we've said that we would make sure that overall from a company perspective, we would continue to drive connectivity and to make sure that our PC business allows us a base to transition to ARM [ph], nothing has changed in that calculation.
Unidentified Analyst
Okay. And I guess what we think about camp four years -- so I think it's like a DST and a converter on 30's or something. Does that part lie in the transceiver module itself? And then also who are your biggest competitors here? Is it IN5, is Micro-Semi or are there other guys out there or do you have no competitor, whatsoever? And lastly, what percent of your products do you sell to hyperscale guys now; do you know that?
Paramesh Gopi
Chris, first let me answer the first part of the question; and I didn't quite hear the last part. There was a little bit of disturbance, if you can repeat it.

Unidentified Analyst
Sure. So I asked about where this product lies; is it in the transceiver module? I asked who your competitors were in five Micro-Semi or other guys. And then lastly, what percent of your revenue comes from hyperscale?
Paramesh Gopi
Okay, great. First is that it is the heart of the module, it is the silicon that enables the optics to actually go and signals for different entities of light. So it lies right smacking them; number one. Number two, you asked about who are the competitors? We own the closest competitor to us, it's probably Alago [ph] Broadcom and then after that -- we're probably 18 months ahead of INFI [ph] in terms of building something like this. INFI talked about PAM4, I think they did a great job evangelizing it. And they've built, however they built two and four laser types of -- it's not single laser. So that's very important.
Third; you asked about hyperscale. Assume that people who are paying us money, their entire opportunity is all about the risk. Nobody would pay us money for low volume optical [ph]. And then the fourth part of it is; I think -- I'll add to what you asked; a significant portion of this comes because of very large early investments in FinFET Technology. So we had the inside track because we called the data center guys for exchange; we knew that this single laser is going to be the key to volume in this timeframe. The IEEE standardization just pretty much locks the whole thing up for us.
Unidentified Analyst
Great, congrats on the quarter again.
Paramesh Gopi
Okay, thanks Chris. Thank you, operator. I would like to thank our employees for their hard work and our customers and shareholders and their ongoing support. Thanks for joining us today. Have a good evening.
Operator
Ladies and gentlemen, thank you for participating in today's conference. This does conclude the program and you may all disconnect. Everyone have a great day.
